        <name>16.5.3.2 Differentiate a Maclaurin series</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Using differentiation, find the Maclaurin expansion of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\((1-x)^{-3}\)&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;(&lt;em&gt;Hint&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;: \(\dfrac{1}{1-x}=1+x+x^2+\cdots\qquad |x|&amp;lt;1\))&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now, by differentiation, obtain the expansion of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\(\dfrac{1}{(1-x)^2}\)&lt;/span&gt;: &lt;span class="math display"&gt;\[\begin{aligned} \dfrac{1}{(1-x)^2}=\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\left(\dfrac{1}{1-x}\right) &amp;amp;= \dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\left(1+x+x^2+\cdots\right), \\ &amp;amp;= 1+2x+3x^2+4x^3 \end{aligned}\]&lt;/span&gt; Differentiate again to obtain the expansion of &lt;span class="math inline"&gt;\((1-x)^{-3}\)&lt;/span&gt;: &lt;span class="math display"&gt;\[\begin{aligned} \dfrac{1}{(1-x)^3}=\dfrac{1}{2}\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}\left(\dfrac{1}{(1-x)^2}\right) &amp;amp;= \dfrac{1}{2}\left[2+6x+12x^2+20x^3+\cdots\right], \\ &amp;amp;= 1+3x+6x^2+10x^3+\cdots \end{aligned}\]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
